<HEADLINE>
FT  16 APR 91 / International Company News: Chase Manhattan bounces back
with profit of Dollars 117m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHASE MANHATTAN, which seemed just six months ago to be among the most
critically ill of the US retail banks, has bounced back with a near-trebling
of first-quarter earnings.
North America's second largest banking group posted net income of Dollars
117m, or 73 cents a share, up from Dollars 44m, or 20 cents a share, a year
earlier.
Lower funding costs and an increase in high-margin consumer lending pushed
up net interest income to Dollars 841m, from Dollars 814m. Fees and
commissions rose by 8 per cent to Dollars 380m, including a 25 per cent jump
in consumer banking charges.
Although non-performing loans continue to loom large in the bank's business,
Chase's chairman Mr Tom Labrecque said he was 'encouraged' by the latest
results.
Analysts were especially heartened by the improved control over operating
expenses, which fell by 2 per cent to Dollars 936m.
Total assets slipped to Dollars 100.5bn from Dollars 107.3bn. However,
return on both assets and shareholders' equity improved markedly, in the
latter case from 2.3 to 10.1 per cent.
Although Chase's earnings were roughly in line with recent forecasts, its
share price climbed 88 cents to Dollars 18.50 yesterday on the New York
stock exchange. The share price is now almost double the low reached last
year when the group sharply cut its dividend to reflect spiralling loan
losses, especially in US real estate.
Mr Stephen Berman, banking analyst at County NatWest in New York, said
yesterday that 'there is some light at the end of the tunnel. Their problems
don't seem to be totally out of control'.
Chase had mixed news regarding problem loans. On the one hand, non-accrual
commercial real estate loans continued to mount, rising to Dollars 2.1bn on
March 31, from Dollars 1.8bn last December and Dollars 884m a year ago.
Other domestic non-accrual loans climbed to Dollars 761m from Dollars 723m
last December.
Non-accrual loans now stand at 4.9 per cent of assets, compared to 4.6 per
cent three months ago, and 3.8 per cent last year.
However, the rate of increase in loan write-offs slowed - and in some types
of business was reversed - during the first quarter.
Loan-loss provisions were Dollars 240m, up from Dollars 225m a year earlier.
Actual loan write-offs, net of recoveries, totalled Dollars 270m, down from
Dollars 325m. The latest figure includes Dollars 19m in write-offs on third
world debt refinancings compared to Dollars 191m a year earlier.
Compared to the previous three months, write-offs on domestic commercial
real estate and other non-consumer loans fell slightly in the latest
quarter. However they remain far higher than a year ago.
Losses on consumer loans continued to rise, reaching Dollars 112m in the
latest quarter, up from Dollars 106m three months earlier.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
