<HEADLINE>
FT  16 APR 91 / Question mark over US insurers
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
ALMOST 500 US insurance companies have had a question mark placed against
their claims-paying ability in a new survey published yesterday by Standard
&amp; Poor's, the large US ratings agency.
Although many of the 489 companies - drawn from both the life and
property/casualty sectors - are small, they wrote an aggregate Dollars
18.3bn-worth (Pounds 10.3bn) of premiums in 1989.
The report comes close on the heels of last week's action against the main
operating unit of First Executive, the large Los Angeles-based insurer which
was taken over by the Californian state regulators.
The action by regulators was the largest-ever seizure of an insurance
company.
S&amp;P stressed that not all of the companies were necessarily in danger, but
suggested their financial condition was 'below average' and they 'deserve
close attention'.
The agency's findings come at a sensitive time for the US insurance
industry.
The issue of solvency regulation - and whether the state regulatory system
is adequate or whether a Federal agency should be set up - has been under
scrutiny for many months.
Full story, Page 26
