<HEADLINE>
FT  16 APR 91 / Arts: Herodiade - Queen Elizabeth Hall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Chelsea Opera Group gave on Sunday a concert performance of Massenet's
Herodiade that was nearly as successful as their Thais a few years ago. The
achievement was only a lesser one in the way the work itself is: whereas
Thais, a chamber drama for all its touches of exotic spectacle, contains its
Grand Opera gestures within a beautifully economic account of human
sexuality and human frailty, the earlier opera gives rather too often the
impression of attempting to 'do an Aida' - to the detriment of Massenet's
most valuable gifts.
These included - as the best parts of Sunday's concert proved beyond
argument - the ability to make sensuously curling melody and the intimate
portrayal of characters in a state of weakness part of the same dramatic
impulse. The principals of Herodiade, an opera some way 'after Flaubert' and
before Wilde and Strauss, are a candidly innocent Salome (soprano), whose
mother abandoned her in childhood, a Baptist (tenor) not unaffected by her
charms (it is not she who clamours for his head), a clamorous, doubt-torn
Herodias (mezzo) who discloses her relationship to her supposedly long-lost
daughter in the opera's closing bars), and a Herod (baritone) openly in
pursuit of the young girl. Whenever the four and their linked affections are
dramatised in close-up, all four-square brassiness disappears.
In such passages, the potency of Massenet's feeling for music-drama is not
in question. Certainly, the strengths of Sunday's reading were connected
with the quartet of leading characters. The casting was imaginative: young
British or British-based singers, all able to deliver reasonable-sounding
French - in the case of Brian Bannatyne-Scott's Phanuel and Rosa Mannion's
Salome, better than that - and all able to temper large phrases with
delicacy and shapeliness. By contrast, while the COG chorus and orchestra
mustered their energies impressively under Michael Lloyd's vigilant baton,
the Grand Opera outward trappings seemed dated and secondhand.
The most complete Massenites of the evening were Anne-Marie Owens
(Herodias), whose wide-ranging, lustrous mezzo is now well fitted for a
whole host of big 19th-century roles, and Mr Bannatyne-Scott, whose velvety
tones are filling out without forcing, and whose sense of style is
impeccable. Forcing at the top was the single flaw of Miss Mannion's
charming, notably musical Salome; to Massenet's dramatic-tenor Baptist,
Graeme Matheson-Bruce brought dignity and power at climaxes, if not much
cantabile grace.
Peter Sidhom, suffering a throat infection, was nevertheless a strong,
firm-toned Herod. The smaller parts were well taken by (among others)
Glenville Hargreaves and Katrina Makepeace-Lott. On such an evening as this
Chelsea Opera Group seem as necessary to London musical life as ever.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-5181</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BDPBVABDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910416
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 APR 91 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC1's drama series about a lawyer whose partner has absconded with the
firm's cash, Kinsey, is proving quite a superior bit of entertainment.
Kinsey's smirking competitor, who was appointed as minder by the Law
Society, has been replaced by pretty Miss Mabbott. Kinsey was awfully shirty
with her last week so he must be about to fall for her (9.30).
The word 'investigative' is used loosely to describe too many sorts of
journalism, including the kind practised in Taking Liberties (9.50 BBC2).
Exculpatory journalism might be a better description: the championing of
people who have fallen foul of the law or been wrongly judged guilty.
Today's episode considers difficulties in suing for medical damages.
Channel 4's 'Banned' season includes a look at current Soviet comedy in From
Russia With Laughter (10.00) and then Monty Python's Life of Brian, a film
which should not be watched by Christians whose faith is so weak that they
cannot bear jokes about their religion.
</TEXT>
