<HEADLINE>
FT  16 APR 91 / Scots tests strongly opposed by parents and teachers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN SCOTLAND, well over half of all pupils do not take part in compulsory
primary school testing as a result of opposition from parent and teachers
alike, James Buxton writes. The Scottish Office is impotent to influence
events.
In Strathclyde Region, which accounts for nearly half the Scottish
population, more than 65 per cent of parents have withdrawn their children
from the tests, which are being applied to seven and 11-year-olds in English
and mathematics.
Similar withdrawal rates are reported from several other regions.
Many teachers are refusing to administer the tests, raising the likelihood
of disciplinary action by their employers, the regional councils.
In what is becoming a political and educational disaster for the government,
the Scottish Office has found it cannot oblige children to sit the tests.
They are subject to different legislation from that in England.
Parents and teachers object to the tests because they believe they threaten
to dilute the universal comprehensive system in Scotland, leading to crude
comparisons between schools and between pupils.
</TEXT>
