FT  16 APR 91 / TV-am to discuss links with Sky news operation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TV-AM, THE breakfast television company, plans to explore links with Sky
News, the 24-hour satellite news channel, when the current franchise bids
finish.
There have already been talks between Mr Bruce Gyngell, TV-am managing
director, and Mr Sam Chisholm, managing director of British Sky
Broadcasting, on potential co-operation.
Both are directors of the Channel 9 television network in Australia and see
opportunities for economies of scale in their UK television news operations.
For example, although TV-am broadcasts just under 3 1/2 hours a day, its
news operation has to be staffed round the clock.
Mr Gyngell is concentrating on regaining the breakfast franchise and will
bid on the existing structure of news provision, but he clearly believes
that co-operation with Sky and the resulting savings could avoid affecting
the station's programme obligations. That could enable TV-am to bid higher
in the competitive tenders that will decide the franchises.
A link with TV-am might help BSkyB, a consortium in which Pearson, publisher
of the Financial Times, has a significant stake, to cut the costs of its
news service. In spite of the cost, senior management at BSkyB see Sky News
as an integral part of its five-channel service.
TV-am is likely to face two well-funded rivals for its franchise.
