FT  16 APR 91 / First fraud case data published by SIB
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SECURITIES and Investments Board, the financial services regulatory
body, has carried out more than 600 investigations since it was created
three years ago. Of those, four have led to convictions, it disclosed
yesterday.
Twenty cases of unauthorised trading involving several million pounds of
investors' money are at various stages of investigation or trial. Two more
cases are to be tried this year.
The SIB's first reported statistics since its inception in 1988 showed the
state of breaches of Section Four of the 1986 Financial Services Act. That
section requires anyone carrying out investment business to be authorised by
the SIB.
'We think we have acted promptly after notification of possible frauds,'
said Mr Jeff Thomas, deputy director of the enforcement division. 'But
clearly there is a lot of fraud not yet detected.'
Officials pointed out that only about half the cases referred to the SIB
turned out to involve an investment business. They warned that individual
investors should be more vigilant.
Mr Thomas said investors should seek proof that the firm was authorised, and
be suspicious of any businesses offering unusually high returns. Most
defrauders do not advertise, he added.
</TEXT>
