FT  15 APR 91 / G7 meeting on post-war world economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PROSPECTS for the world economy after the Gulf war and the collapse of
communism in eastern Europe were last night assessed in informal talks in
London by finance ministers from the Group of Seven leading industrial
nations.
No substantive statements were made after the discussions which took place
over an informal dinner at 11 Downing Street hosted by Mr Norman Lamont, the
chancellor.
The UK Treasury said the ministers had 'very good and useful discussions on
a wide range of subjects.'
Mr Theo Waigel, the German finance minister, said afterwards: 'We have had a
good meeting as always.'
Although the ministers from the US, Japan, Germany, France, Italy, Britain
and Canada left the meeting in good humour, it appeared that several
contentious issues were raised in the discussions.
On entering Number 11, Mr Waigel confirmed that he had come to London intent
on raising the question of 'burden sharing'. This issue of how the big
industrial countries should share the global economic costs of Middle East
reconstruction after the Gulf war and the reconstruction of eastern Europe
has become increasingly controversial in the G7.
Germany believes it is getting insufficient recognition for its efforts to
help eastern Europe and the Soviet Union.
There was also evidence yesterday of tension between the US and Japan, which
was believed to reflect US dissatisfaction with Japan's contribution to Gulf
war costs.
Mr Ryutaro Hashimoto, the Japanese finance minister, described a longer than
expected bilateral meeting with Mr Nicholas Brady, the US treasury
secretary, earlier in the day as 'a friendly argument'.
