<HEADLINE>
FT  15 APR 91 / Observer: Still going
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
One of the more remarkable things about US money managers is how many of the
go-go investors of the swinging Sixties are still hanging around. Last
week's seizure of Los Angeles-based Executive Life, which has shaken the US
insurance world, has focused attention on one of the great survivors:
60-year-old Fred Carr.
A veteran of the Ira Haupt-salad oil fiasco of the early 1960s, he used to
run the Enterprise Fund which for a while was one of the hottest mutual
funds around. He then moved into the more conservative world of insurance in
the early 1970s. His recent problems stemmed from the fact that he bought
too many junk bonds from the late Drexel Burnham Lambert.
Although no one has heard of Bernie Cornfeld for a long time, several of
Carr's con-
temporaries are still around. Admittedly, Gerry Tsai's star has never shone
as brightly again as it did in the 1960s, but Fred Alger has an
above-average record and Howard Stein, of Dreyfus fund managers, is a pillar
of respectability.
</TEXT>
