<HEADLINE>
FT  15 APR 91 / UK News (Employment): Team working urged in clothes sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TEAM WORKING, rather than assembly lines, can offer substantial benefits to
clothing manufacturers seeking to supply shorter runs and respond more
quickly to requirements, according to a report from the National Economic
Development Office.
The report studies six companies using team working in the UK, US and
Germany. It investigates issues such as ideal team sizes and whether
part-time workers are suitable.
Team working, sometimes called modular manufacturing, is when a group of
workers carries out interchangeable work, for which there may be a general
bonus. Three large British garment manufacturers - Coats Viyella, Courtaulds
and Bairdwear - have team working in some operations.
The report identifies several drawbacks with assembly line work on the new
shorter runs. Take-home pay fluctuated because workers had to learn new
styles. That could lead to workers' seeking alternative employment. Also
evidence was growing that machinists who mainly performed a single operation
were likely to be particularly susceptible to repetitive strain injuries.
Team working: A guide to modular manufacturing in the garment industries.
Nedo Books, Millbank, London SW1P 4QX. UK price Pounds 25 plus Pounds 1.20
p&amp;p.
Tootal war of words, Page 18
</TEXT>
