<HEADLINE>
FT  15 APR 91 / UK News (Employment): Union row over N Sea pay deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A DISPUTE between leaders of unofficial industrial action in the North Sea
and official unions broke out publicly yesterday as union leaders said they
were prepared to sign a pay and conditions deal that would fall short of the
terms they originally demanded.
Leaders of the Amalgamated Engineering Union responded sharply to criticism
of union tactics from the leaders of unofficial action. Mr Gavin Laird, AEU
general secretary, said the criticism was 'singularly unfortunate' and would
inhibit union recruitment.
In spite of efforts to get most of the 20,000 contract workers to register
with unions in order to hold a ballot on industrial action, AEU leaders said
only 7,000 had registered. That meant the ballot would have to be postponed
indefinitely.
Talks between unions representing contract construction workers and leaders
of offshore contracting companies are due early this week. Among those
taking part will be Mr Jimmy Airlie, AEU executive councillor, and Mr Tom
McLean, the construction section national secretary. Mr Airlie said he would
be prepared to sign a deal providing conditions were met.
That would mean unions would re-enter an agreement covering work on 'hook
up', or the construction of rigs, which they abandoned two years ago because
employers would not extend union recognition to the 'post-hook-up' phase of
rig maintenance.
They would accept instead a model set of terms and conditions from the
Offshore Contractors Council in return for undertakings including an end to
the alleged blacklisting of 460 workers who took part in industrial action,
and the right to recruit workers offshore.
That stance has been strongly criticised by the Offshore Industry Liaison
Committee because the unions have accepted that they will not be able to
obtain a broad continental-shelf deal covering all North Sea workers.
Leaders of unofficial action are this week expected to announce that they
may form a non-TUC union covering oil and gas workers.
Mr Airlie said that a continental-shelf agreement remained a long-term aim
of unions but they had to accept that they were not yet strongly organised
enough to achieve it.
The AEU leaders were speaking at the start of the Scottish Trades Union
Congress in Dundee yesterday.
</TEXT>
