<HEADLINE>
FT  15 APR 91 / UK News (Employment): Study shows mental health problems of
City dealers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CITY DEALERS working for US-owned financial institutions are likely to
suffer from poorer mental health and find their jobs less satisfying than
counterparts in more conservative UK companies, psychologists have found.
Results of the survey, carried out in 12 institutions with 200 dealers, were
presented to the annual conference of the British Psychological Society by
Dr Howard Kahn of Heriot-Watt University.
Female dealers were better able to cope with work-related stress, although
they experienced less job satisfaction. In spite of better academic
qualifications, women reported general discrimination and fewer promotion
opportunities.
More than 40 per cent of dealers questioned in an initial survey said they
drank heavily, compared with 8 per cent of other professionals.
Dr Kahn said: 'Though it appears that dealers are able to cope with the long
hours and pressures associated with their work, their high intake of alcohol
. . . the pattern of relaxation at and after work with colleagues, and the
lack of support outside work gives rise to concern.'
</TEXT>
