<HEADLINE>
FT  15 APR 91 / UK News (Employment): TUC proposes role in product
improvement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By OUR LABOUR EDITOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNIONS were yesterday urged to make use of new management techniques in
order to establish a role in improving product quality. The call came in a
paper published by the TUC as part of the most fundamental review of its
role for a quarter of a century.
In the paper, which will be central to discussions among union leaders this
year, unions are advised to learn as much as possible about human resource
management (HRM) and total quality management (TQM) techniques in order to
gain from them.
An analysis of trade unionism in the 1990s by Lord McCarthy, a Fellow of
Nuffield College, Oxford, argues that although most workers are sceptical of
HRM, the techniques stem from managers' acceptance that people are not
merely another factor of production.
Lord McCarthy says that some overt attempts to improve involvement and
commitment 'turn out to be ways of loading (workers) with additional
responsibilities without appropriate changes of job description or
upgrading'. However, he says the increased awareness that working people are
the key to organisational efficiency can be seen 'as an opportunity to show
that unions can contribute constructively to the pursuit of total quality'.
He also says unions can make pay demands that reflect their members'
contribution to improved performance and lower unit costs. They may be
accompanied by 'more flexible and speedy procedures for resolving
outstanding differences'.
TUC Towards 2000, A Consultative Document. TUC, Congress House, Great
Russell Street, London WC1B 3LS. Pounds 5.60.
</TEXT>
